---
import PageHead from "@/components/PageHead.astro"
import { SOCIAL_LINKS } from "@/consts"
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro"
import { Icon } from "astro-icon/components"

const githubHref =
  SOCIAL_LINKS.find((link) => link.label === "GitHub")?.href ?? "#"
const linkedinHref =
  SOCIAL_LINKS.find((link) => link.label === "LinkedIn")?.href ?? "#"
---

<Layout class="max-w-3xl">
  <PageHead slot="head" title="About" />
  <section class="mt-12">
    <div class="flex flex-col items-center text-center">
      <img
        src="/static/logo.svg"
        alt="Logo"
        class="h-24 w-24 rounded-full"
        loading="eager"
      />
      <h1 class="mt-6 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">About Me</h1>
      <div
        class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4 text-sm font-semibold"
      >
        <a
          href={githubHref}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer noopener"
          aria-label="GitHub"
          class="brutal-link inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-semibold"
        >
          <Icon name="lucide:github" class="h-5 w-5" />
          GitHub
        </a>
        <a
          href={linkedinHref}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer noopener"
          aria-label="LinkedIn"
          class="brutal-link inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-semibold"
        >
          <Icon name="lucide:linkedin" class="h-5 w-5" />
          LinkedIn
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert mt-12 max-w-none">
    <p>
      Nearly eight years ago, I fell down the Linux rabbit hole (and watching
      Matrix may or not may not have been a part of it). I was drawn to free and
      open source software, to the idea that every layer of the system was
      visible, and configurable
    </p>
    <p>
      I broke everything, and then I would spend hours rebuilding what I had
      just destroyed. Somewhere in that cycle of breaking and rebuilding, I
      started to get interested in development
    </p>
    <p>
      Programming grew naturally out of that environment. At first it was small
      scripts. Then tools. Then projects. If something did not exist, I could
      build it, and just thinking of something and implementing it became very
      enjoyable
    </p>
    <p>
      Today, I am pursuing a bachelors degree in computer science while
      continuing to build as much as I can. Also focusing on pulling my old
      projects from the grave and now adding them to my portfolio
    </p>
    <p>
      I would call myself a jack of all trades, though probably more of a deuce.
      Either way, my girlfriend finally got me to stop sitting on this and
      actually start writing, so here we are. Looking forward to seeing where it
      goes
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
